00:07:37.330 --> 00:07:38.840
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Exactly.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:40.590
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: And I wonder if
you could talk a little bit more

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:42.700
about how you came to
name the book that.

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:44.000
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Gladly.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:45.730
And you said it exactly right.

00:07:45.730 --> 00:07:50.780
I wanted that sense of
another country, James Weldon,

00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:55.840
within a country, a separate
and yet overlapping land.

00:07:55.840 --> 00:07:58.040
I chose the word Negro

00:07:58.040 --> 00:08:02.570
because capitalized it was the
honored and preferred term.

00:08:02.570 --> 00:08:07.590
As I'm sure people of an older
generation in this audience know.

00:08:07.590 --> 00:08:15.240
For basically early 20th
century to mid to late '60s,

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:19.650
the Harlem Renaissance
talked about the New Negro.

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:22.750
The New York Times
began capitalizing it.

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:25.020
This was a big fight in the '30s.

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:30.770
But that was the honored word
during my coming of the age years

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:34.160
and I wanted to use that as a way

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:42.350
of helping recreate the
culture of being a Negro.

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:47.750
And in the world I was in,
which was the Negro bourgeoisie

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:51.760
which called itself-- like to call
itself an upper class or an elite,

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:54.270
you know, being a Negro meant--

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:58.020 position:56%
it's what people call
respectability politics today trying

00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:03.770
to be a perfect emblematic--
emblematically intelligent,

00:09:03.770 --> 00:09:05.850
dignified, representative
of your race.

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:08.980
And this went, you
know, into everything

00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:12.400
from your speech patterns,
to your manners, to, in fact,

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:19.450
in my Chicago version of that
world, having decent race politics,

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:21.640
you know, advancing the race.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:26.240
So all I wanted to capture
those rituals that tone.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:31.750
Land is an interesting word because
lands have their own culture,

00:09:31.750 --> 00:09:36.420
each land, which we did
as American Negroes.

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:41.710
But lands are also bordered by
others, sometimes hostile lands.

00:09:41.710 --> 00:09:44.060
And, you know, the
very segregated world

00:09:44.060 --> 00:09:50.630
of Chicago contained various kinds
of black life all bordering on

00:09:50.630 --> 00:09:56.830
and often menaced by
white lands, if you will.

00:09:56.830 --> 00:10:01.150
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: So what--
I'm curious as a writer.

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:05.940
When you-- When is it that you
decided to write this memoir?

00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:10.000
And how long were you writing it
before you actually committed words

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.300
to paper?

00:10:11.300 --> 00:10:13.030
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Oh,
that's a good question.

00:10:13.030 --> 00:10:15.170
You are an editor, aren't you?

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:16.880
All right.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:20.380 position:56%
So your first one is when did began?

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:21.680
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Decide.

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:22.980
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
Decide, all right.

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:24.820
You know, often when
you're a writer, you know,

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:26.370
you're going about your business

00:10:26.370 --> 00:10:28.330
like some people you're
turning out books.

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:30.910
I was turning out articles.

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:34.570
But, you know, material
keeps building up.

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:39.490
And as particularly my parents
got older and as I, you know,

00:10:39.490 --> 00:10:44.430 position:56%
got through my rebellions and began
to trust myself in relation to them,

00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:48.690
every time I visited Chicago,
their world became more

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:53.370
and more interesting to me because
I could bring an adult person

00:10:53.370 --> 00:10:57.670
and writer's eye to it
and look back at all--

00:10:57.670 --> 00:11:02.250
look at all the rituals and
manners and ways and expressions.

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:07.430 position:56%
They were carrying on, you know,
and realized, "Oh, my God, you know.

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:09.110
This has to be preserved.

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:11.360
This is fascinating."

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:15.380
And Isabel Wilkerson captures
that, you know, all that so well

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:17.760
in her book "The Warmth
of Other Suns",

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:22.740
so many ways of talking,
thinking, dressing.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:24.740
So that's I think when it started--

00:11:24.740 --> 00:11:29.800
probably I started taking notes in
the '70s or '80s but did not at all

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:32.850
yet commit myself,
commit my imagination

00:11:32.850 --> 00:11:36.060
or my consciousness to a book.

00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:42.020
In-- Not until the 2000s really
did I decide I have to do this.

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:45.460
Zoey Mil Harrison [assumed
spelling] has a great line about--

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:48.240
she's talking about needing
to tell a story as a writer

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:54.200
and she says there's the Roman
legend of the boy who that was

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:59.780
