00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:33.800
often life gives you
a kind of urgency.

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:37.880
I thought I have to record
everything I can while she's alive

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:42.270 position:56%
but also, you know, because I don't
know how long any of them will live.

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:43.570
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Right.

00:12:43.570 --> 00:12:44.870
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Yeah.

00:12:44.870 --> 00:12:46.170
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: What-- So was she
able to see any part of your book?

00:12:46.170 --> 00:12:48.440
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: She saw part of
it, yes, she didn't see the whole

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:50.180
and she helped a lot, you know.

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:53.680
Siblings, relatives, you have
different kinds of memory

00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:59.020
and she had very acute sense memory
and also just things to compare--

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:00.320
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Right.

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:01.620
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: -- against.

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:02.920
So that was good.

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:04.220
And my mother-- my
father died first.

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:07.380
My mother is incredibly sharp
and witty and I was constantly--

00:13:07.380 --> 00:13:13.210
I'd be on the phone with her and
I'd be typing down her witticisms.

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:14.510
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Right, right.

00:13:14.510 --> 00:13:22.090
So when we-- you know, you've
taken us into this second country

00:13:22.090 --> 00:13:26.910
in our country of the black
elite, the black bourgeoisie.

00:13:26.910 --> 00:13:32.220
And the geography, the map you draw
