00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:34.930
Many white people think
we weren't even raped.

00:15:34.930 --> 00:15:37.490
We were just loose and flatteringly

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:39.910
on the plantations
and after, you know.

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:41.280
We don't really have minds.

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:43.380
We're just lusty, sexy creatures.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:49.980
All of those stereotypes, we're
still circulating in the, you know,

00:15:49.980 --> 00:15:52.740
through the whole-- through
most of the 20th century.

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:55.390
They only started changing
in the late '60s.

00:15:55.390 --> 00:15:59.180
So, you know, that--
those kinds of history--

00:15:59.180 --> 00:16:04.230
histories are hanging over you when
you go out to eat in a restaurant,

00:16:04.230 --> 00:16:05.880
when you sit down in a
school room, you know.

00:16:05.880 --> 00:16:12.510 position:56%
When-- Anytime you enter any part of
the white world, at the same time,

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:21.620 position:56%
you know, we were fighting that
self hatred by honoring black people

00:16:21.620 --> 00:16:26.350
and their history and yet
because of class prejudice,

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:29.850
you are also cultivating
real kinds of snobbery

00:16:29.850 --> 00:16:33.510
as every bourgeoisie
is taught to do.

00:16:33.510 --> 00:16:36.170
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Except the
dress really nice for you today.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:38.330
[ Laughter ]

00:16:38.330 --> 00:16:40.500
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Oh, God.

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:42.020
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Just teasing.

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:43.690
Actually I do--

00:16:43.690 --> 00:16:47.110
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: And you
look very fabulous in deed.

00:16:47.110 --> 00:16:48.410
Yes.

00:16:48.410 --> 00:16:49.710
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Go on.

00:16:49.710 --> 00:16:51.010
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
You are so [inaudible].

00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:54.280
So it's that kind of
self consciousness,

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:58.850
the struggle between pride and
self hatred and the struggle

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:07.080
between honor and snobbery,
I would say, right, it's key.

00:17:07.080 --> 00:17:09.360
And consciousness, you know.

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:14.050
Black power was a big struggle for
the black-- for the Negro elite.

00:17:14.050 --> 00:17:15.350
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Right.

00:17:15.350 --> 00:17:16.650
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Not so
much from my generation.

00:17:16.650 --> 00:17:19.040
We were thrilled to seize it.

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:25.530
But nevertheless, it felt like you
had to remake yourself entirely.

00:17:25.530 --> 00:17:30.730 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: All the internal
scrutiny, I wonder about what it was

00:17:30.730 --> 00:17:33.200
like as a child, one of the things

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:40.860 position:56%
that I found rather sad is the
pressure for children to figure this

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:42.630
out and to navigate the world

00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:44.870
of through this two
worlds in which they live.

00:17:44.870 --> 00:17:46.170
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Yeah.

00:17:46.170 --> 00:17:47.550
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: It seemed very
challenging and also the struggle

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:51.060
for parents, for African
American parents the whole idea

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:54.400
of preserving innocence
as long as you can.

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:55.810 position:56%
I wonder if you can talk about that.

00:17:55.810 --> 00:17:57.110
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: There is.

00:17:57.110 --> 00:17:58.410
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: And
comparing it now,

00:17:58.410 --> 00:18:01.450
do you still see the
remnants of that?

00:18:01.450 --> 00:18:02.750
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
You know, every--

00:18:02.750 --> 00:18:05.270
I'm wondering if I
can find this passage

00:18:05.270 --> 00:18:09.950
from the wonderful black historian
and writer James Weldon Johnson

00:18:09.950 --> 00:18:14.580
where he describes
exactly the pressures.

00:18:14.580 --> 00:18:17.200
Well, I don't want to spend huge
amounts of time looking for it

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:21.910
but he says, "For every Negro
parent," and his writing this

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:26.130
in the '30s, "there is this
battle, internal battle

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:33.070
between keeping a child, you know,
innocent enough to feel confident

00:18:33.070 --> 00:18:34.870
about moving through the world.

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:37.780
And yet if you are a black child,

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:41.440
making sure you know
enough about prejudice."

00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:45.300
We see played out, acted out in--

00:18:45.300 --> 00:18:49.400
you know, in terms of the police
brutality cases all the time

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:52.220
when parents say, "What am
I going to tell my son?"

00:18:52.220 --> 00:18:53.910
you know, going through this.

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:56.510
Well, there also, you know,
plenty of other things.

00:18:56.510 --> 00:19:00.100
Parents are worrying about
telling a black child.

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:04.700
So you know, that balance is
always, do you tell too little,

00:19:04.700 --> 00:19:08.000
do you tell too much,
do you tell it too soon.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:11.810
And James Weldon Johnson
has a chilling line.

00:19:11.810 --> 00:19:15.020
He says, "Either way if
you go too far either way,

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:18.370
it can spell spiritual disaster
for the child," you know,

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:22.690
which is psychologically as
well as sociologically profound.

00:19:22.690 --> 00:19:29.400
And every generation of black
parents inherits what their parents

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:32.820
did or didn't-- and didn't
do with them and then has

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:36.410
to renegotiate it according
to the historical

00:19:36.410 --> 00:19:39.710
and sociological circumstances.

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:43.480
I was not-- my sister and
I we were very protected

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:44.780
in that world in many ways.

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:48.060
We were not physically threatened.

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:51.880
What our parents had
to navigate, you know,

00:19:51.880 --> 00:19:54.550 position:56%
were things like-- it's in the book.

00:19:54.550 --> 00:19:56.890
Well, we go to-- we're
on a vacation,

00:19:56.890 --> 00:20:00.050
we go to a hotel in Atlantic City.

00:20:00.050 --> 00:20:03.740
They suddenly can't
find the reservations.

00:20:03.740 --> 00:20:06.040
My father says, "Dr. Jefferson."

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:09.390
The hotel clerk keeps saying,
"Mr. Jefferson, I can't find it."

00:20:09.390 --> 00:20:12.940
Finally, we got shown
to an egregious room.

00:20:12.940 --> 00:20:16.360
You know, and my sister
and I still don't get it.

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:19.620
My parents, you know, are--
they don't want to tell us

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:22.090
but they are letting us
know we're leaving tomorrow.

00:20:22.090 --> 00:20:23.450
It's a prejudice hotel.

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:25.590
The bathtub is dirty.

00:20:25.590 --> 00:20:27.940
There are those kinds of things.

00:20:27.940 --> 00:20:32.070
Also, we have to navigate
and integration.

00:20:32.070 --> 00:20:36.700 position:56%
And by the time especially you get--
you know, do you do play dates?

00:20:36.700 --> 00:20:38.060
Now, this is the '50s.

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:42.500
So let's not forget in the
'50s, the Brown versus Board

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:46.070
of Education is just happening.

00:20:46.070 --> 00:20:50.840
So, you know, these little worlds
of this or that, private school

00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:54.010
or public school, the private
ones were more sheltered.

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:58.490
They were-- Everyone
was feeling their way.

00:20:58.490 --> 00:21:00.650
So, yeah, do you do play dates?

00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:02.460
When you do, are you reading

00:21:02.460 --> 00:21:05.160
that the mothers are really not
comfortable with each other?

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:06.850
And do you make of that.

00:21:06.850 --> 00:21:09.180
When adolescence comes,
the whole question

00:21:09.180 --> 00:21:12.180
of interracial dating comes up.

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:14.860
And, you know, the parents--
all parents have to decide,

00:21:14.860 --> 00:21:19.010
I don't want my black child
to be hurt or belittled

00:21:19.010 --> 00:21:20.520
or exonecized [phonetic].

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:23.870
But the child has-- is going
to be doing and thinking

00:21:23.870 --> 00:21:25.400
and experimenting with things.

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:29.440
I, the parent, did not and
they must have room, you know,

00:21:29.440 --> 00:21:32.040
to move into the world
as it changes.

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:35.720
That is still going on, of course.

00:21:35.720 --> 00:21:41.610
You know, life-- well, you know,
it depends on where you are

00:21:41.610 --> 00:21:46.460
and how much, you know, money
and access and privilege

00:21:46.460 --> 00:21:48.360
in terms schools, neighborhoods.

00:21:48.360 --> 00:21:52.650
The black parents were
talking about have, actually.

00:21:52.650 --> 00:21:54.500
I can't give one answer
to that question.

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:59.650
But the negotiations, of
course, are still continuing.

00:21:59.650 --> 00:22:00.950
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: You're right.

00:22:00.950 --> 00:22:04.260
Your book has been called and
described as brave and revelatory.

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:08.680
And there is-- there
are a couple of moments

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:10.830
in the book that are very poignant.

00:22:10.830 --> 00:22:15.370
The level of stress for you, you
talked about and being in college

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:21.110
and wanting to avoid offensing
program and practicing--

00:22:21.110 --> 00:22:23.140
throwing yourself down the
step so that you could--

00:22:23.140 --> 00:22:25.040
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: So that I
could say I had a real injury.

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:26.340
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Yes.

00:22:26.340 --> 00:22:34.300
Exactly. But more poignantly
was this idea that you consider,

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:37.240
thought about suicide quite a lot.

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:42.170 position:56%
And I wanted to know how the process

00:22:42.170 --> 00:22:44.730
by which you decided
to write about that.

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:46.380
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: All right.

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:52.760
One, you know, suicide
is a very private matter.

00:22:52.760 --> 00:22:57.620
But I decided I wanted to write
about it for several reasons.

00:22:57.620 --> 00:23:03.050
The easiest reason to state
first, I think is, and I am--

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:07.150
well, first the statement
then the qualification.

00:23:07.150 --> 00:23:11.340
One of the stereotypes,
interestingly enough

00:23:11.340 --> 00:23:15.450
that black people contend
with or one of the sets

00:23:15.450 --> 00:23:23.090
of expectations is you're supposed
to be too strong to be depressed,

00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:27.070
you know, to breakdown, to
be acknowledged any kind

00:23:27.070 --> 00:23:30.190
of unhappiness that's
certainly the way many,

00:23:30.190 --> 00:23:35.000
many black people are
raised, you know.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:36.370
Don't give way.

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:42.560 position:56%
To give way in anyway to acknowledge
defeat, grief, melancholy,

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:46.020
depression, is to give
the white man,

00:23:46.020 --> 00:23:48.330
to give white people the victory.

00:23:48.330 --> 00:23:52.630
I grew up very much in
that landscape which,

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:54.980
you know, really comes several.

00:23:54.980 --> 00:24:01.010
Certainly, it's totally forms in
the 19th century it precedes that.

00:24:01.010 --> 00:24:08.780 position:56%
And I found it enormously burdensome
as I moved into my life as a writer.

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:13.990
I found when I spoke honestly
to black friends of my, again,

00:24:13.990 --> 00:24:17.400
particularly women that I
saw it manifested in men

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:20.420
that they were often
suffering the same--

00:24:20.420 --> 00:24:23.880
from the same thing and
yet the business of therapy

00:24:23.880 --> 00:24:27.870
or counseling, that very forbidden.

00:24:27.870 --> 00:24:32.160
So, you know, so much of this book
is about what in terms of the--

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:36.530
you know, one's matriculation
into adult, you know, blackness,

00:24:36.530 --> 00:24:41.920
you know, what's forbidden,
what's accepted, you know, what--

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:47.030
how do you-- what's allowed, what
room for improvisation is allowed.

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:48.540
You know, what's the relationship

00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:52.780
of each black individual
to the group at large.

00:24:52.780 --> 00:24:55.900
So that's one reason I wanted
to write openly about it,

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:57.940
to help break that taboo.

00:24:57.940 --> 00:25:02.790 position:56%
And I am finding many of my
students, you know, people of color,

00:25:02.790 --> 00:25:07.640
Blacks but also Latins,
South and East Asians.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:12.380
At Columbia are-- they're
writing about this kind of thing

00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:14.020
and responding to it also.

00:25:14.020 --> 00:25:18.270
It's been a kind of big
cultural social secret.

00:25:18.270 --> 00:25:21.860
The other thing is, if
you're writing a memoir,

00:25:21.860 --> 00:25:24.720
you do choose what
material to leave out.

00:25:24.720 --> 00:25:26.020
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Yes.

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:30.980
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: But a real--
But living within the confines of

00:25:30.980 --> 00:25:36.100
and negotiating with
depression, which is as much anger

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:40.880
at it is grief had been a very
large part of my adult life

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:45.630
and it was just too much of
a lie, not to write about it.

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:49.130
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: And I see we
have about five more minutes.

00:25:49.130 --> 00:25:52.970
So there's a question that
I wanted to really get to.

00:25:52.970 --> 00:25:56.080
And it's about the
quote for your mother.

00:25:56.080 --> 00:25:58.810
It's a very strong quote.

00:25:58.810 --> 00:26:01.240 position:56%
And she says very early in the book.

00:26:01.240 --> 00:26:03.960
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Yeah, my-- This
is also at my-- they just placed.

00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:06.800
My mother and my father
are young-- married.

00:26:06.800 --> 00:26:12.760
It's 1943, there at Fort
Huachuca, the all black army fort.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:14.780
And my mother is writing.

00:26:14.780 --> 00:26:16.520
She's pregnant with my sister.

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:18.140
She's only been married
a couple of years

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:20.920
and she is writing a
dear friend of hers.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:22.220
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Yes.

00:26:22.220 --> 00:26:24.990
And she writes to her friend in
the closing part of the letter.

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:28.520
"Sometimes I almost
forget that I am a Negro.

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:31.160
That's something, huh."

00:26:31.160 --> 00:26:32.460
Talk about the statement--

00:26:32.460 --> 00:26:33.760
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
Oh, wait a minute.

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:35.060
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: -- and
what that means to you?

00:26:35.060 --> 00:26:37.940
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: What proceeds
that is that she is saying

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:42.990
to her friend, you know, there's
another of hers is about is engaged

00:26:42.990 --> 00:26:46.700
and my mother is saying, please,
you know, give her my best

00:26:46.700 --> 00:26:49.430
and tell her I wish her
all the happiness I have.

00:26:49.430 --> 00:26:52.300
In fact, I have so
much happiness now

00:26:52.300 --> 00:26:54.620
that sometimes I almost
forget I'm a Negro

00:26:54.620 --> 00:26:56.780
and that's something [inaudible].

00:26:56.780 --> 00:26:59.180
I found that letter--
or my mother found it

00:26:59.180 --> 00:27:01.470
and showed it to me in the '70s.

00:27:01.470 --> 00:27:07.090
And I read it out loud in
our kitchen to my sister

00:27:07.090 --> 00:27:09.710
and my then quite young niece.

00:27:09.710 --> 00:27:12.560
And we are joy drunk.

00:27:12.560 --> 00:27:18.970
It was so poignant my mother
had always been very meticulous

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:24.620
about what in terms of racial--
we could see her anger at times.

00:27:24.620 --> 00:27:31.730
But racial grief, you know, that
sense of helplessness at times.

00:27:31.730 --> 00:27:33.250
She was-- no.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:35.450
We did not see.

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:40.240
So to read this and realize that,
you know, the rest of the letter is

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:44.120
about movies she's seeing and
sorority doing, then clothes

00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:50.750
and books and to see suddenly in
that line all of the pressures,

00:27:50.750 --> 00:27:55.120
you know, that she had lived with.

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:59.000
She and every other black
person coming of age,

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.320
you know, had lived with.

00:28:01.320 --> 00:28:06.010
And yet to see that she was a
full, charming, and lovely person

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:12.840
and had seized all of these things
that you can take for granted

00:28:12.840 --> 00:28:17.520
from falling in love
with someone to loving,

00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:22.020
seeing the movie "Jane
Eyre", she had claimed those

00:28:22.020 --> 00:28:25.560
for herself even though
in some way we

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:28.720
as black people didn't
quite have licensed--

00:28:28.720 --> 00:28:30.020
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Yeah.

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:31.320
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
-- to those pressures.

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:32.620
That's what I see that
sentence is mean, yeah.

00:28:32.620 --> 00:28:33.920
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Yeah.

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:36.120
I read as she had found
a way to be fully human--

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:37.420
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Yeah.

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:38.720
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: -- in a
world that one of the things

00:28:38.720 --> 00:28:40.940
that racism does is
it denies humanity--

00:28:40.940 --> 00:28:42.240
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Exactly.

00:28:42.240 --> 00:28:43.540
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: -- and
you're total humanity.

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:44.860
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: And
it can force you to feel--

00:28:44.860 --> 00:28:46.500
it's a crime never to forget.

00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:47.800
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Yes.

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:49.100
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: And she
was saying I can do both.

00:28:49.100 --> 00:28:51.360
I can remember and forget.

00:28:51.360 --> 00:28:52.660
Yeah.

00:28:52.660 --> 00:28:53.960
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: So you
mentioned your niece.

00:28:53.960 --> 00:28:58.970
How did you help her navigate
this world as she was growing up?

00:28:58.970 --> 00:29:01.750
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Well, I
followed my sister's lead.

00:29:01.750 --> 00:29:05.820
Of course, you have to be
careful as [inaudible] her uncle

00:29:05.820 --> 00:29:09.300
because I'm sure some of you know.

00:29:09.300 --> 00:29:14.710
Again, I think what we both tried
to do, what I was most aware

00:29:14.710 --> 00:29:19.290
of was she wanted to
dance, she was musical,

00:29:19.290 --> 00:29:24.250
really encouraging everything in
her temperament and personality

00:29:24.250 --> 00:29:28.590
that signaled flourishing, you
know, and to give her a sense.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:31.350
I always had her keeping
a little notebook.

00:29:31.350 --> 00:29:33.950
Not because she was going to
become a writer necessarily,

00:29:33.950 --> 00:29:39.360 position:56%
but because as a girl also, I wanted
her to feel her thought mattered,

00:29:39.360 --> 00:29:43.050
you know, that she could have
observations about anything.

00:29:43.050 --> 00:29:49.190
In terms of race, we try to follow
the James Weldon Johnson lead.

00:29:49.190 --> 00:29:52.080
She took ballet lessons very early.

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:56.560
And so my sister really had
to navigate between, you know,

00:29:56.560 --> 00:30:02.350
encouraging the hard work and
the discipline and the pleasure

00:30:02.350 --> 00:30:06.770
that if you love ballet, it can
give you nevertheless and the fact

00:30:06.770 --> 00:30:10.080
that it was a very,
very white world.

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:13.480
My niece, oh, eventually danced
with the Frankfort Ballet

00:30:13.480 --> 00:30:16.050
and the Dance Theater of Harlem.

00:30:16.050 --> 00:30:17.780
But she's 46 now.

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:21.030
You know, there would not have
been room for her in ballet theater

00:30:21.030 --> 00:30:22.620
as there is now for
wonderful [inaudible].

00:30:22.620 --> 00:30:23.920
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Right, yes.

00:30:23.920 --> 00:30:25.220
Right, yeah.

00:30:25.220 --> 00:30:26.650
Do you think white--

00:30:26.650 --> 00:30:30.290
This is something that my
friends and I debate so often.

00:30:30.290 --> 00:30:34.230
It's just like do you think white
Americans think about race as much

00:30:34.230 --> 00:30:36.480
as African Americans
think about race?

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:39.120
Do they even think about us as
much as we think about them?

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:40.420
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: Well--

00:30:40.420 --> 00:30:43.350
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Maybe some
of you can answer that, too.

00:30:43.350 --> 00:30:45.180
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
Yeah, maybe you should.

00:30:45.180 --> 00:30:48.680
You know, it depends on
the white Americans, right.

00:30:48.680 --> 00:30:50.110
Doesn't it, she said.

00:30:50.110 --> 00:30:53.420
I would say what-- you know,
this is not something new.

00:30:53.420 --> 00:31:00.340
One of the privileges of being--
of taking your identity and status

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:07.920
for granted is not having to
think about the complexities,

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:11.060
the contradictions, the
difficulties of it all the time.

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:16.640
One of the reasons we are
seeing this venomous backlash

00:31:16.640 --> 00:31:20.880
of racism going in multiple
directions, you know,

00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:25.860
is that certain groups of white
people are finding that they're--

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:28.630
when they think about their
identity, they are thinking

00:31:28.630 --> 00:31:31.260
about challenge, depravation,
you know,

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:36.260
not getting what they used to-- you
know, it's all being rattled up.

00:31:36.260 --> 00:31:41.460
But I think traditionally,
white people have been able

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:49.400 position:56%
to choose much more when they wanted
or needed to think or interested in

00:31:49.400 --> 00:31:54.390
or even in terms of certain social
forces had to think about it.

00:31:54.390 --> 00:31:55.910
Then, you know, if you live

00:31:55.910 --> 00:31:58.310
in in all white neighborhood,
you could closed out.

00:31:58.310 --> 00:32:01.800
You could-- I think it's
becoming harder now.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:05.610
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: Sure the Obama
presidency has also made it--

00:32:05.610 --> 00:32:06.910 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson: I think it was--

00:32:06.910 --> 00:32:08.210
&gt;&gt; Marcia Davis: -- an issue.

00:32:08.210 --> 00:32:09.510
&gt;&gt; Margo Jefferson:
It was galvanizing

00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:10.810
in good and very bad ways.

00:32:10.810 --> 00:32:13.770
It brought a lot of stuff racially

00:32:13.770 --> 00:32:16.960
